<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1946-01-02T07:30:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1946-01-02T07:30:00-05:00" n="208" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d208">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">891.00/1–246: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Iran</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Murray</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                            </seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Tehran</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1946-01-02T16:00:00+03:30">January 2,
                                    1946—4 p.m.</date>
                                <lb/> [Received January 3—11:36 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>10. Rossow<note n="11" xml:id="d208fn11">Robert Rossow, Jr., Vice Consul
                                at Tabriz.</note> in Tabriz confirms fall of Rezaieh and end of Iran
                            Govt resistance in Azerbaijan. He states that Kurds aided Democrat
                            forces not Iranian Army as local press had reported.</p>
                        <p>Sent Dept as 10, repeated Moscow 5.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Murray</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>